\begin_layout Title
Tackling (mis)perceptions about the consumption-related traits of improved
 crop varieties: the case of cooking and tasting demonstrations in Uganda
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
As part of a larger study on producer and consumer-side interventions for
 increasing adoption of improved crop varieties, we conducted a qualitative
 inquiry to learn about the consumption-related traits and consumer preferences
 for improved maize varieties in Uganda.
 This is an area with far less empirical work so far, since most studies
 evaluating strategies to promote agricultural technology adoption focus
 on traits and constraints on the producer side.
 Throguh a co-learning workshop and gender disaggregated focus group discussions
, we consulted thirty six maize consumers in Eastern Uganda on: (i) whether
 and how consumers can identify differences between maize varieties when
 they consume maize in different forms; (ii) what consumers consider as
 the most important maize consumption-related traists, and why these traits
 are important; (iii) the maize varieties in their communities that are
 most suitable in terms of the stated traits; and (iv) whether consumption-relat
ed traits influence farmers' choice of the maize variety to grow.
 We learned that maize is mainly consumed in the forms of posho meal, porridge,
 and whole maize (boiled or roasted), and that consumers can identify difference
s between varieties mainly through taste, color of the grain/flour, and
 size/weight of the grain.
 Maize consumption-related traits that are most important to consumers are
 palatability (sweet and smooth taste), grain size/weight (bigger/heavier
 grains produce more flour and also weigh more during selling), and flour
 productivity (ability of the flour to expand and produce more posho to
 feed more people).
 Using social network analysis, Bazooka maize variety emerged as the improved
 variety most suitable for these traits, followed by Longe 10H and Longe
 5.
 Finally, we find that farmers also consider consumption-related traits
 (mainly grain size/weight, milling-out-turn, and taste) when choosing a
 (new) maize variety to grow, although this is after ascertaining the yield
 potential.
 Maturity time of a variety is also important but mainly considered as a
 consumption-related trait because this ensures timely availability of maize
 for both food and income.
\end_layout

