\begin_layout Standard
The workshop had nineteen maize consumer participants, and was held prior
 to the FGDs.
 We conducted four FGDs in the communities, to follow-up on the key feedback
 from the workshop.
 Two of the FGDs consisted of men and women, interviewed separately.
 The third and fourth FGDs were mixed (both men and women), of which, one
 consisted only a couple (husband and wife).
 The number of FGD participants ranged between two (couple) to six.
 A gender focus during the FGD discussion was important, especially after
 learning from the workshop that men and women are aware of, and seemingly
 prefer different maize consumption-related traits.
 We also learnt from the workshop that men and women are involved in different
 activities of the maize consumption processâ€” for instance, women do more
 of the cooking, while men are more responsible for taking maize for milling.
